Reva Meyers Glushien
</div><div id='commentItem18' class='commentItem' style='background-color: '>18. <span style='font-style: italic;'>George L Gombasy</span> says:<br /><small>7 Dec 2014 10:44:09 AM</small><br /><br />My father , Louis G Gombasy was with the Nevada at Pearl Harbor and received the Navy Cross for his actions.  I am looking for anyone who has any information as to those actions other than in the official citation. I welcome any comments or opinions as to why he was singled out as there certainly many individual's actions that were equal in nature and at similar risk. </div><div id='commentItem19' class='commentItem' style='background-color: #f0f0f0'>19. <span style='font-style: italic;'>Barry Fernandez</span> says:<br /><small>6 Dec 2016 09:15:44 AM</small><br /><br />Looking for info on my step-dad Alfred Cicillini and Cecil Macloud (my wife's Granddad). Both were cooks on the USS Nevada when it was bombed on Dec 7th 1941.</div><div id='commentItem20' class='commentItem' style='background-color: '>20. <span style='font-style: italic;'>Peter J. Skiba</span> says:<br /><small>15 May 2017 01:06:14 PM</small><br /><br />My Dad Pete Skiba was on the USS Nevada during the Pearl Harbor attack. His usual assignment was as a mailman. I believe that under attack there was probably another assignment for a mailman to assume. Does anyone know what that assignment was? Any help greatly appreciated. </div><div id='commentItem21' class='commentItem' style='background-color: #f0f0f0'>21. <span style='font-style: italic;'>thomas hoffstetter</span> says:<br /><small>22 May 2017 10:28:24 AM</small><br /><br />My father,James hoffstetter also was at Pearl hbr Dec 7 1941 on the nevada.his rate , gunners mate- believe his service started w/ this ship. Later transfered to the uss phoenix - also any info would help</div><div id='commentItem22' class='commentItem' style='background-color: '>22. <span style='font-style: italic;'>gerald  goudie</span> says:<br /><small>22 Jun 2017 12:17:32 PM</small><br /><br />My dad, Ray Goudie, was a Fire Controlman for the main batteries.  He served on the Nevada shortly before Pearl Harbor, through D-Day to the end of WWII.  He was one of the men responsible for the "legendary" accuracy of her big guns.  After I retired from the military I became friends with Capt. Don Ross, winner of the Medal of Honor.  My wife and I loved talking with him about his experiences on the Nevada.</div><div id='commentItem23' class='commentItem' style='background-color: #f0f0f0'>23. <span style='font-style: italic;'>Greg Kachoeff</span> says:<br /><small>14 Aug 2017 11:26:44 PM</small><br /><br />My father Arthur Kachoeff served on the Nevada from I believe Normandy, through the Pacific theater and also volunteered to serve at the Bikini bomb testing. I still have his cherished Nevada book, and formal black uniform. I'm very proud of him and his many friends whom I had the pleasure of meeting through the years of his life. </div><div id='commentItem24' class='commentItem' style='background-color: '>24. <span style='font-style: italic;'>Karen Kent</span> says:<br /><small>23 Sep 2017 02:48:32 AM</small><br /><br />looking for a crew list for the uss nevada for dec 7, 1941. </div><div id='commentItem25' class='commentItem' style='background-color: #f0f0f0'>25. <span style='font-style: italic;'><img src='/images/icon_check.png' height='11' alt='Commenter identity confirmed' title='Commenter identity confirmed' />&nbsp;David Stubblebine</span> says:<br /><small>23 Sep 2017 11:50:10 PM</small><br /><br />Karen Kent (above):<br />The crew lists you speak of were called Muster Rolls by the Navy and they can be viewed at Fold3.com. There was not a Muster Roll specific to 7 Dec 1941 but the regular quarterly Muster Roll would have been completed on 31 Dec 1941. The previous Muster Roll would have been prepared 30 Sep 1941 with monthly updates of any intervening changes. Also, Muster Rolls only listed enlisted men; officers were accounted for in the Deck Log which are not available online so far as I know.</div><div id='commentItem26' class='commentItem' style='background-color: '>26. <span style='font-style: italic;'>Jim Jensen</span> says:<br /><small>8 Feb 2018 04:51:10 PM</small><br /><br />My father served aboard BB36 from before Pearl till the end of the war. I have been trying to locate the final resting place of the ship. Several write ups say it was sunk southwest of Hawaii. However, a 2004 documentary shows an under water shot of the stern of NEVADA in a lagoon in the Marshall islands. Does anyone know the accurate location ?</div><div id='commentItem27' class='commentItem' style='background-color: #f0f0f0'>27. <span style='font-style: italic;'><img src='/images/icon_check.png' height='11' alt='Commenter identity confirmed' title='Commenter identity confirmed' />&nbsp;David Stubblebine</span> says:<br /><small>8 Feb 2018 11:33:51 PM</small><br /><br />Jim Jensen (above):<br />The Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships describes Nevada being sunk as a target ship off Hawaii 31 July 1948. Navy photo #80-G-498282 shows the ship sinking with a caption saying the same thing.</div><div id='commentItem28' class='commentItem' style='background-color: '>28. <span style='font-style: italic;'>Bobbi Johnson</span> says:<br /><small>3 Mar 2018 06:14:04 PM</small><br /><br />Several years ago I found a flag at a local Goodwill. Hated seeing it there languishing, I purchased it, brought it home and was surprised at several things - it was on a cane pole, it had forty-eight stars and more than half of it is stained with oil. I get the feeling it was at Pearl Harbor on December 7th. Is there anyway to look at the crew compliments of those ships and cross match them with personnel who might have moved to Minnesota and perished here, especially near St. Paul? </div><div id='commentItem29' class='commentItem' style='background-color: #f0f0f0'>29. <span style='font-style: italic;'>Anonymous</span> says:<br /><small>4 May 2018 01:54:57 PM</small><br /><br />what is the thing in google maps that said uss neveda bb36 and it is onlty a rock?</div><small><p>All visitor submitted comments are opinions of those making the submissions and do not reflect views of WW2DB.</p></small>	<script>
